<!-- INTRO -->
<section id="intro">
  <div class="reveal">
    <p class="section-label">What Are Chakras</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Wheels of <em>prāṇic</em> energy<br>within the subtle body</h2>
    <p class="prose">The word <strong>chakra</strong> (चक्र) is Sanskrit for "wheel" or "disc" — a term describing spinning vortices of prāṇa (life-force energy) that Yogic and Tantric traditions describe as existing within the <em>sūkṣma śarīra</em>, the subtle or energetic body that underlies the physical form.</p>
    <p class="prose">Classical Hindu philosophy distinguishes three bodies: the gross physical body (<em>sthūla śarīra</em>), the subtle body (<em>sūkṣma śarīra</em>) composed of prāṇa, mind, and intellect, and the causal body (<em>kāraṇa śarīra</em>) of deep unconscious impressions. The chakra system belongs to the subtle body and should not be understood as physical organs detectable through surgery — they are energetic and experiential in nature.</p>
    <p class="prose">It is important to note that the chakra system as popularly known today — especially the seven-chakra rainbow model — is largely a synthesis of Tantric Śaiva texts, Hatha Yoga manuals, and 20th-century Western reinterpretations. The tradition is both ancient and contested; different texts describe different numbers of chakras. What follows is grounded in classical textual sources.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="divider"></div>
  <div class="intro-grid reveal">
    <div class="intro-card">
      <span class="intro-card-icon">स</span>
      <h3>Sūkṣma Śarīra — The Subtle Body</h3>
      <p>Yogic philosophy holds that consciousness operates through a hierarchy of bodies. The subtle body, invisible to ordinary perception, carries the patterns of karma, prāṇa, and saṃskāras (mental impressions) that shape experience.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="intro-card">
      <span class="intro-card-icon">न</span>
      <h3>Nāḍīs — Energy Channels</h3>
      <p>The Hatha Yoga Pradīpikā speaks of 72,000 nāḍīs (energy channels). Of these, three are primary: Suṣumnā (central spine channel), Iḍā (lunar, left), and Piṅgalā (solar, right). Chakras exist as nodal points where these channels intersect.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="intro-card">
      <span class="intro-card-icon">प्र</span>
      <h3>Prāṇa — Life Force</h3>
      <p>Prāṇa is not merely "breath" — it is the animating intelligence behind all biological and psychological processes. The five prāṇas (Prāṇa, Apāna, Samāna, Udāna, Vyāna) govern different regions of the body corresponding to chakra territories.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="intro-card">
      <span class="intro-card-icon">त</span>
      <h3>Tantra — The Theoretical Framework</h3>
      <p>Most chakra knowledge comes from Śākta and Śaiva Tantric texts, not the Vedas or early Upaniṣads. Tantra views the human body as a microcosm of the cosmos — a vehicle for spiritual liberation through the awakening of Śakti (divine energy).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="intro-card">
      <span class="intro-card-icon">यो</span>
      <h3>Yoga — The Practical Path</h3>
      <p>Haṭha Yoga operationalizes chakra theory through āsana, prāṇāyāma, mudrā, and bandha. Kuṇḍalinī Yoga specifically focuses on arousing the dormant energy at Mūlādhāra and guiding it upward through the chakras toward Sahasrāra.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="intro-card">
      <span class="intro-card-icon">मो</span>
      <h3>Mokṣa — The Goal</h3>
      <p>The spiritual purpose of chakra work is not health or emotional wellness in isolation — the classical aim is mokṣa: liberation from the cycle of rebirth. Each chakra corresponds to progressively subtler levels of consciousness on that journey.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SCRIPTURES -->
<div class="section-full bg-dark-1" id="scriptures">
<section style="max-width:1200px; margin:0 auto; padding: 7rem 0;">
  <div class="reveal">
    <p class="section-label">Textual Origins</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What the <em>ancient texts</em><br>actually say</h2>
    <p class="prose">The chakra system was not described in a single definitive scripture but emerged across centuries of Tantric, Yogic, and Āgamic literature. The primary source for the seven-chakra model is the <em>Ṣaṭ-Cakra-Nirūpaṇa</em> (1577 CE), yet earlier texts hint at similar frameworks.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="scripture-grid reveal">
    <div class="scripture-card">
      <div class="scripture-name">षट्चक्र निरूपण</div>
      <div class="scripture-era">Sat-Cakra-Nirupana · 1577 CE · Pūrṇānanda</div>
      <p class="scripture-quote">"There is a lotus of four petals in the region of the mūlādhāra..." — Verse 4</p>
      <p>The definitive classical source for the seven-chakra model. Composed by the Bengali Tantric Pūrṇānanda, it minutely describes each chakra's petals, presiding deities, bīja mantras, and geometrical forms. It is the primary text from which most modern knowledge derives.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="scripture-card">
      <div class="scripture-name">हठयोग प्रदीपिका</div>
      <div class="scripture-era">Hatha Yoga Pradipika · ~14th century CE · Svātmārāma</div>
      <p class="scripture-quote">"Suṣumnā is in the middle, Iḍā on the left, Piṅgalā on the right..." — Chapter 4</p>
      <p>One of the most important Hatha Yoga manuals. Describes the three primary nāḍīs and their relationship to chakra activation, prāṇāyāma, and kuṇḍalinī awakening. Less focused on chakra symbolism, more on the physiological practice.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="scripture-card">
      <div class="scripture-name">शिव संहिता</div>
      <div class="scripture-era">Shiva Samhita · ~17th century CE</div>
      <p>Describes seven chakras and 350,000 nāḍīs. Notable for attributing the text to Lord Śiva speaking to Pārvatī — framing yogic knowledge as divine revelation. It describes chakras explicitly as part of the kuṇḍalinī awakening pathway and emphasizes guru guidance.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="scripture-card">
      <div class="scripture-name">योगकुण्डली उपनिषद्</div>
      <div class="scripture-era">Yoga Kundalini Upanishad · circa 17th century CE</div>
      <p>One of the 108 minor Upaniṣads. Explicitly addresses kuṇḍalinī śakti and its movement through chakras. Importantly, it cautions that this energy must be awakened gradually and only under qualified guidance — a warning often missing from popular accounts.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="scripture-card">
      <div class="scripture-name">विज्ञान भैरव तन्त्र</div>
      <div class="scripture-era">Vijnana Bhairava Tantra · ~7th–8th century CE</div>
      <p>A Kaśmīr Śaiva text containing 112 dhāraṇā (concentration) practices. While not a chakra manual per se, it describes practices of focusing awareness on specific body centers — an indirect textual ancestor of chakra meditation systems.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="scripture-card">
      <div class="scripture-name">तैत्तिरीय उपनिषद्</div>
      <div class="scripture-era">Taittiriya Upanishad · ~600 BCE · Vedic Period</div>
      <p>The Vedic text that describes the Pañcakoṣa model — five sheaths of the self (annamaya, prāṇamaya, manomaya, vijñānamaya, ānandamaya). While not describing chakras directly, this framework of layered bodies is the philosophical foundation on which the chakra system was later built.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
</div>

