<!-- KUNDALINI -->
<div class="section-full bg-dark-2" id="kundalini">
<section style="max-width:1200px; margin:0 auto; padding:7rem 0;">
  <div class="reveal">
    <p class="section-label">Kundalini & Nadis</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The <em>serpent force</em><br>and the three rivers</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="kundalini-wrap reveal">
    <div>
      <p class="prose">Kuṇḍalinī (कुण्डलिनी) literally means "she who is coiled" — from <em>kuṇḍala</em>, a coiled serpent. According to Tantric physiology, this primordial Śakti lies dormant at the base of the spine in Mūlādhāra chakra, coiled three-and-a-half times around Svayambhu Liṅga, a subtle energetic form.</p>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <p class="section-label" style="margin-top:0">The Three Primary Nāḍīs</p>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-symbolic">Suṣumnā</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">The central channel running through the spinal column from Mūlādhāra to Sahasrāra. When Iḍā and Piṅgalā are balanced through prāṇāyāma, Suṣumnā opens and kuṇḍalinī can ascend. This is the primary pathway of spiritual awakening.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-spiritual">Iḍā</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">The lunar nāḍī, associated with the left nostril, cooling energy, introspection, feminine principle, and Śiva consciousness. Governs the parasympathetic dimension of experience.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-science">Piṅgalā</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">The solar nāḍī, associated with the right nostril, heating energy, activity, masculine principle, and Śakti. Governs the sympathetic dimension and extroversion.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <p class="section-label" style="margin-top:0">Traditional Cautions</p>
      <p class="prose">Classical texts are uniform in warning that kuṇḍalinī awakening should not be forcibly induced. The Yoga Kuṇḍalinī Upaniṣad, the Shiva Saṃhitā, and modern teachers like Swami Sivananda all emphasize that premature or unguided awakening can produce severe psychological and physical disturbances — described in Yogic literature as <em>prāṇic crises</em>.</p>
      <p class="prose" style="margin-top:1rem">The guru-disciple relationship (paramparā) was designed precisely to transmit these practices safely. Contemporary literature on <em>kuṇḍalinī syndrome</em> documents real cases of individuals experiencing disorientation, somatic disturbances, and psychiatric symptoms following intensive unsupervised practice.</p>
    </div>
