<!-- ACTIVATION -->
<section id="activation">
  <div class="reveal">
    <p class="section-label">Traditional Methods</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Paths of <em>awakening</em></h2>
    <p class="prose">Classical Yogic texts describe a range of interrelated practices for purifying the nāḍīs and activating the chakras. None of these is a quick fix — they are described as requiring years of disciplined practice under guidance. Modern wellness adaptations often strip away the ethical prerequisites (yama-niyama) that traditional systems consider foundational.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="practice-grid reveal">
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="practice-icon">प्र</span>
      <h4>Prāṇāyāma</h4>
      <p>Regulation of prāṇa through breath control. Nāḍī Śodhana (alternate nostril breathing) is considered the primary practice for balancing Iḍā and Piṅgalā and preparing Suṣumnā for kuṇḍalinī ascent.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="practice-icon">मं</span>
      <h4>Mantra & Japa</h4>
      <p>Repetition of bīja mantras associated with each chakra (Laṃ, Vaṃ, Raṃ, Yaṃ, Haṃ, Om). Sound vibration is held to directly resonate with the subtle energy of each center, stimulating activation over time.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="practice-icon">मु</span>
      <h4>Mudrā & Bandha</h4>
      <p>Mudrās are symbolic gestures that redirect prāṇic flow. The three bandhas (Mūla, Uḍḍīyāna, Jālandhara) create energetic locks that intensify and direct the flow of prāṇa upward through Suṣumnā.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="practice-icon">आ</span>
      <h4>Āsana</h4>
      <p>Physical postures that develop the body's capacity to hold and channel energy. Specific āsanas affect specific chakras — e.g., Mūla Bandha āsanas for Mūlādhāra, heart openers for Anāhata.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="practice-icon">ध्य</span>
      <h4>Dhyāna</h4>
      <p>Meditation involving sustained, concentrated awareness on a chakra's location, symbol, deity, or quality. Distinguished from casual visualization — classical dhyāna requires stable prāṇāyāma practice as its foundation.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="practice-icon">भ</span>
      <h4>Bhakti</h4>
      <p>Devotional practice directed toward the deity or principle associated with a chakra. Opening Anāhata, for instance, is closely linked in bhakti traditions to practices of compassion, devotion, and seva (selfless service).</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SCIENCE -->
<div class="section-full bg-dark-1" id="science">
<section style="max-width:1200px; margin:0 auto; padding:7rem 0;">
  <div class="reveal">
    <p class="section-label">Science & Tradition</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Four lenses for<br>understanding <em>chakras</em></h2>
    <p class="prose">Intellectual honesty requires distinguishing between what ancient texts claim, what modern science has verified, what psychological frameworks can explain, and what remains genuinely open. Conflating these produces both bad spirituality and bad science.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="dual-col reveal">
    <div>
      <p class="chakra-section-head">Tradition says</p>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-spiritual">Textual</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">Chakras are real energetic structures within the subtle body, detectable through refined awareness developed in deep meditation practice — not through physical instruments.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-spiritual">Textual</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">Activation of chakras produces genuine transformation of consciousness — not metaphorical change, but actual shifts in perception and identity.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-spiritual">Textual</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">The system is experiential and initiatory — its truth is verified through practice, not debate. The texts themselves say this.</span>
      </div>
      <p class="chakra-section-head" style="margin-top:2rem">Science finds</p>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-science">Scientific</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">No physical structures corresponding to chakras have been identified through anatomy, neuroimaging, or biophysical measurement. No reproducible empirical evidence for subtle bodies as described in Yogic texts.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-science">Scientific</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">Meditation neuroscience (Newberg, Davidson) documents real changes in brain activity, cortical thickness, and autonomic regulation from sustained practice — but these are explained by neuroscience without requiring the chakra framework.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-science">Scientific</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">The claimed physiological correspondences (Mūlādhāra = adrenal glands, etc.) are modern retrofits with no classical textual basis — a projection of Western endocrine science onto an older framework.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p class="chakra-section-head">Psychology suggests</p>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-symbolic">Symbolic</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">Carl Jung noted structural parallels between chakra symbolism and individuation stages — the chakras may describe a universal archetypal progression of psychological development, independent of their metaphysical status.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-symbolic">Symbolic</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">Somatic therapists (Peter Levine, Bessel van der Kolk) work with body-held emotional patterns that map loosely onto chakra territories — suggesting the body stores experience in region-specific ways.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-symbolic">Symbolic</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">The framework provides a language for mapping inner experience. Its clinical value may lie in providing structure and narrative for psychological processes that are otherwise difficult to articulate.</span>
      </div>
      <p class="chakra-section-head" style="margin-top:2rem">What remains open</p>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-symbolic">Open</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">The hard problem of consciousness — the nature of subjective experience — remains unsolved by science. The claim that subtle energy systems exist in dimensions not accessible to current instruments is unfalsifiable in the technical sense, which means it is neither proved nor disproved.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="distinction-row">
        <span class="distinction-badge badge-symbolic">Open</span>
        <span class="distinction-text">Thousands of practitioners across cultures report consistent experiential phenomena during deep meditation that correspond to classical chakra descriptions. This anecdotal consistency is noteworthy even if its interpretation remains contested.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
</div>

